This is a ordered sequence of refelctions on the process of building the DoggyApp. Many are being done well after the time that I wrote the code but these are the learning expereinces that stuck with me. 

Cloud Formation Development
I was struck by how well developed the AWS documentation is. Using CLoudFormation you are able to see all details of the configuration of the resource you are 
provisioning, these details link to fuller documation on the details of each resource and service, and it is all layed out in yaml format so you can just understand 
it at the level of what you're coding by looking at it. Choosing to begine with CloudFormation was a good choice becuase it gave me a full grasp of the configuration 
option of each resource a provided a detailed understanding of the capabilities and use of the AWS platform. Still to this day whenever I need to provision something 
I will default to writing the code in CloudFormation and deploying it from there. This way I only have to memorize a single command, I can specify all details of the 
resource I am provisioning and know exactly what it is and delete it afterwards with the assurance that all traces of it will be gone, with the added benefit of being 
ability to see all of my resources in the CloudFormation console, my full 1 stop location to see all resources in my entire AWS environment. If a resource fails to 
deploy I can see the stack trace and if I need to automate its deployment I can put it into an Ansible Script. It is so incredibly helpful to have everything written 
down, to know what it is, and to automate its deployment, and also to be able to pass variables out of CloudFormation and into Ansible so that they can be used in a 
larger script. 

Debugging CloudFormation 
Keeping track of variables is key in CloudFormation, you need to make sure that variable names are passed properly so that dependencies can build on each other. 
It can become a bit of a convoluded mess whe you have to take a variable out of the Stack, pass it into the Master File, then from the Master file and into another 
Stack, and there are three different stacks that all have a dependency that needs to be passed in. This was a source of mild frustration where a variable name didn't ]
match. AI has been helpful in solving this, it is a simple thing for an AI to just check variable names and make sure that they are consistent, becuase it is just a 
"grep" command for them. But there are also architectural challenges the first being permissions AWS IAM roles and users need to be crafted to make sure that the CF 
script is able to run. At one point I was manually running the pipeline for my K8s cluster over and over and copy pasting the perission error (containing the missing
permission) into my IAM role for the pipeline. This was painful, but better than allowing * permissions. Stack Overflow and online tutorials were a helpful resource 
to get myself off the ground, AI was much less developed at the time, and for something as important as permissionos I wouldn't entirely trust it becuase I wouldn't 
want my personal account to be suseptable to escalation attacks. But the process familiarised me with tracing logs in CF and using them to debug. It also familiarised 
me with the different permissions used in EKS, EC2, Secrets, Keys and other services.

CodePipeline 
This was my first taste of CI/CD it gave me knowledge of the different build phases. I was surprised that all it is is running linux commands. I saw that Code Build 
provisions a linux instance. Then you run to Lint and build commandd and are able to see the logs for each command so you can follow where it broke. Lint runs a 
simple linter over the CF code to make sure that it is valid, then builds the master yaml file for CF, saves it to an S3 Bucket which can be used for versioning, 
though I didn't, and then CodePipeline takes that built file and runs it though CF to deploy. I really got a sense of how useful this was by developing the script 
in tandem with the Pipeline. Like it made the whole process so much faster to just press a button and see if it works, and to get specific logs and visions on where 
the breakdowns were happening. I don't understand how anyone ever built anything functional without a pipeline. It was also good to see the security that goes in 
place in a pipeline, creating web hooks, adding permissions to the GitHub API and handling keys. The whole process of validating the process, a lot can be automated, 
but security cannot be, becuase it requires a human who owns the process to allow the automation. 

