Kubernetes Set Up 
This was a difficult one to wrap my head around. I had done simple things like written pods and services locally, but there is a lot more going into a cloud deployment. 
One of the first decision I had to make was a log collection and if i would hook my cluster up to CloudWatch or other AWS services i decided not to becuase of the cost. 
I felt that I hadn't run into a use case for it yet and so I would cross that bridge when I got there. I did end up using grafana and prometheus for monitoring later 
though after i had built the cluster the first thing I wanted was insight into it so that coudl see in detail what it was that I had built and how it was working. I 
felt that as the development process continues this sort of insight (especially as this was the first cluster I had built and I didn't know what I was doing), would be 
valuable. However the first hurdle was accessing the cluster. I was trying to use my Admin User profile to access the cluster naively thinking that it had permissions 
to EKS all resources and so that would allow me to enter. This was not the case. You need the role of the Entity or user who created the cluster to access the RBAC. 
This meant that I needed to use my pipeline role (the creating entity) to access the RBAC. From here I was able to edit the RBAC to add the Admin user to the cluster 
and begin management of it. With this the Admin has access to EKS commands (outlined in the IAM role), and now also has RBAC access to the Kube commands (the EKS 
commands will not run without RBAC access, though you can run Kube commands without IAM permissions but with RBAC). But with the Admin having access to both this role 
was able to set up periferal AWS services to enable the full set up of the cluster. Additionally, this Admin requires sign on and 2-factor authenitcation (using IAM 
Idenitty Center) securing the Cluster behind a sturdier wall. The Ansible script for this is in the Kubernetes Architecture. 

Ansible 
Writting an Ansible script was incedibly helpful for the process of deploying the application. Not only does it resure me that i fix any issue if I accidently delete 
something I shouldn't (which I did once). It also means that (in the early stages) I can delete my entire application and redploy it exactly as it was. It seems like 
good hygene to have a record of all changes that can be reimplemented at any point. The key being that it is indempotent, meaning that no matter what breaks you can 
run the script and it will fix it and leave everything else as is. It is the ultimate tool for self healing and version control. The flip side to this is that I also 
have a Breakdown script that will delete everything. This gives me great peace of mind to know that I will have no remaining surprise billing from stragling resources. 

Prometheus Grafana Loki 
In this setup I encorporated monitoring, as I said I felt it important to have insight into what I had built. I was unfamiliar with the technology I was using and 
for all I knew it could be experiencing disastrous error having all sorts of problems. For this I learned about Helm. It was an extremely convenient tool for 
provisioning the monitoring suit. All I had to do was write the configuration scripts correctly as it was able to implement them. What I found suprising about this 
process was how modular it was, I just have to input the correct file names for where the logs where coming from and wire it up to Loki's API, then wire up Loki's API 
to the Prometheus end point. You can deploy all of these in any order and it will work, none of them are dependent on each other. The worst that will happen is that 
messages get sent to an end point that doesn't exist. 

The second thing that struck me was how versatile the prometheus language is for detecting key words in logs and generating alerts off of them. I was mainly curious 
about how to use them and knowing that my application was going to be published to the open internet I decided to create simple alerts that detected the word 
"error" in my Spring and Angular applications, hoping to catch any foul play or just problems with the application. 

The alerting pod 
It was awesome to see in real time how helpful monitoring is for security. I connected my montoring suit to a Gunicorn webhook which took these alerts fed them through 
OpenAI and sent me information on what caused them. No sooner did this go live than I started recieving multple alerts in my Angular application from bots entering 
URLs into my application like "/production-server". This prompted me to learn more about what was going on and how to resolve the issue. I had no idea that these 
things where everywhere for one. But also I figured out that the best practice for dealing with it was to create a "not found" page where these sorts of requests 
could gracefully go fuck themselves. I also implemented rate limiting on the Loadbalancer. This expereince does give me a new appreciation for teh depth that log 
analysis can go, this was a very simple script and caught a very simple attack, and I realise the need for more knowledge on how to implement stronger log analysis 
to catch more complex attacks, and also to be aware that logs can be altered and to incorporate metrics into a defensive posture. 

