GitLab 
This was anothing thing that AI was helful for, I asked it to write detailed instructions for how to set up GitLab and they were mostly right, but I definately had to
do a lot of leg work to research how to set it up, so I could understand is indepently from an AI synopsis, to ask questions about process and to make my own 
architectural decisions that contradicted the instructions that were fed me. GitLab works the same as CodePipeline in essense. You run a bunch of Linux commands in 
order. The difference was in the complexity of making it run on Kubernetes and as a service hosted on my bastion rather than having that leg work done for me by AWS. 
This entailed installing GitLab on my instance and giving it the permissions TO BE ACCESSED BY the runner and AgentK, there are 2 separate tokens needed to do this. The 
agent token and the runner token. The Runner token is like the Linux instance that runs the build script in CodePipeline, it executes the commands, builds an image 
and sends it to ECR. It then sends the deploy command back to GitLab running on my bastion which readies it for AgentK to call, AgentK is a pod with a RBAC permission 
to access the Kube API, UNDER A NARROW BAND OF CONFIGURED CONDITIONS (that the GitLab instance has the proper Token and that the project being deployed is in the configured
allow list). 

Application Architecture 
The application started out monolithic but I quickly realised that it made more sense to break it up into 3 different microservice. The nature of the application of owners
connecting dogs with care organisations to employees under those organisations handling the dogs made it clear that there werer 3 different sets of users, owners, 
organizations and emplyees. Each of these three groups would use the application at different rates, for different purposes, and with different amounts of each type of 
user. A single monolithic architecture for that wouldn't be very sensible. So In the frontend I created 3 services, owner service, user service and organization service 
and I created a backend or each service. This meant that each service handle a single type of user and that each user can authenticate to their repecive backend. 

