Security Considerations in the application 
there were a few benchmarks I wanted to hit and I was checking the AI make sure that they were done correctly. 
1. I wanted the passwords to be encrypted 
2. I wanted the makesure that PII wasn't leaked so I checked the sessions against the database in eveery API call so that it was certain that if someone was lookinng at a 
piece of information it was tied to what they should be allowed to look at. Like when an Owner calls GetDog to see their own dog the api call is not GetDog(dogId) it is 
GetDog(dogID, OwnerID), and it validates against the database the sessions of the logged in owner that they can only see their own dog. 
3. I made sure that there was Password validation on the frontend, I used NIST guidelines, the recommendation being that you check the password not for complexity but 
against a list of the most commonly bruteforced passwords to make sure that it is not easily guessed I used an inbuilt dependency in Angluar for this zxcvbn. I chose 
to do it this way because as a short cut when I was developing I didn't add password validation, and made all of the test passwords "pass" just to make life easier for 
myself. My Norton password manager saved this and 3 second later notified me that my password had been stolen. So I deleted all of the users in my database and started
over with proper validation, using my password manager to save these passwords. 
4. SpringSecurity is configured to only accepts traffic originating from the doggyapp.click address, hopefully meaning that XSRF attacks will be styied. 
5. I registered an address for the site so that I could attach a certificate to it and connect it to my loadbalancer. This means that it is HTTPS. Which was suprisingly 
easy to do with AWS and Kubernetes as the core technologies. 

Cost 
I wanted to be able to afford to host this, so I provisioned the Kube node instances as spot instances and this has shaved off half the cost from my monthy expenses
and only at the cost of kubernetes having to repovision them for me, which it does automatically given that I gave it an Autoscaler through helm. 

Next step 
The Autoscaler that I gave it has backfired on me. For high avaiablity I configured my cluster to extend 2 availability zones, US-East-1a and Us-East-ib. But I provisioned 
by database on an EBS file, this only extends to 1 availablity zone. Meaning that when my stateful set was torn from the spot instance and reestablised in a differnt AZ 
The database failed, becuase the block storage was in the wrong place. For true high availablity I will need to switch from EBS to something better like EFS. 

